SIMPLE: intensity
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Intensity
<hw>In*ten"si*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>intensitas</ets>: cf. F. <ets>intensit⟦eacute⟧</ets>. See
<er>Intense</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The state or quality of being intense; intenseness;
extreme degree; <as>as, <ex>intensity</ex> of heat, cold, mental
application, passion, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If you would deepen the <qex>intensity</qex> of light, you must be
content to bring into deeper blackness and more distinct and definite
outline the shade that accompanies it.</q> <rj><au>F. W.
Robertson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>The amount or degree of energy
with which a force operates or a cause acts; effectiveness, as estimated
by results produced.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>The magnitude of a distributed
force, as pressure, stress, weight, etc., per unit of surface, or of
volume, as the case may be; <as>as, the measure of the
<ex>intensity</ex> of a total stress of forty pounds which is
distributed uniformly over a surface of four square inches area is ten
pounds per square inch</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Photog.)</fld> <def>The degree or depth of color or
shade in a picture.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intensive</ent>⟦br⟧
